573.title: Transitive relation
573.clickbait: If a is related to b and b is related to c, then a is related to c.
573.text:
A binary [-3nt] $R$ is **transitive** if whenever $aRb$ and $bRc$, $aRc$. 

The most common examples or transitive relations are [3rb partial orders] (if $a \leq b$ and $b \leq c$, then $a \leq c$) and [53y equivalence relations] (if $a \sim b$ and $b \sim c$, then $a \sim c$).

A transitive relation that is also [5dy reflexive] is called a [-preorder].

A [-transitive_set] $S$ is a set on which the element-of relation $\in$ is transitive; whenever $a \in x$ and $x \in S$, $a \in S$.

70f.title: "Is this what is meant by transitive and nontran..."
70f.text:
Is this what is meant by transitive and nontransitive set?

Transitive:

$A = \{ \{ 1,2 \}, \{ 3,4 \}, 1, 2, 3, 4 \}$

$x = \{1,2\}$

$a = 2$

$a \in x$, $x \in A$ and $a \in A$

Nontransitive:

$B = \{ \{ 1,2 \}, \{ 3,4 \} \}$

$y = \{1,2\}$

$b = 2$

$b \in y$, $y \in B$ but $b \notin B$

70k.title: "Yes, that's correct. I wonder if it is even a g..."
70k.text: Yes, that's correct. I wonder if it is even a good idea to talk about transitive sets in the transitive relation page, as most people who are interested in transitive relations are not likely to care about transitive sets. When this page is expanded beyond stub status, I hope that it will focus mostly on transitivity, rather than related concepts such transitive sets, posets, and preorders.
